Below is a DITISS-aligned, CCEE-ready MCQ set covering both sessions together.

üìò Public Key Infrastructure ‚Äì Sessions 11 & 12
Authentication, SSO, OAuth, FIDO & Zero Trust
(PG-DITISS August 2025)

üü¢ BASIC MCQs (10)
1. Authentication is the process of:
A. Granting access rights
B. Verifying identity
C. Encrypting data
D. Logging activity

2. Which is an example of single-factor authentication?
A. Password only
B. Password + OTP
C. Smart card + PIN
D. Biometrics + OTP

3. Multi-factor authentication (MFA) uses:
A. One factor only
B. Two or more authentication factors
C. Encryption algorithms
D. Hashing

4. Which is NOT an authentication factor?
A. Something you know
B. Something you have
C. Something you are
D. Something you encrypt

5. Single Sign-On (SSO) allows users to:
A. Use multiple passwords
B. Login once and access multiple systems
C. Encrypt all sessions
D. Avoid authentication

6. OAuth is mainly used for:
A. Authentication only
B. Authorization
C. Encryption
D. Hashing

7. OpenID is used for:
A. Authorization
B. Authentication
C. Encryption
D. Digital signatures

8. Graphical passwords use:
A. Numbers only
B. Images or visual patterns
C. Tokens
D. Certificates

9. FIDO stands for:
A. Fast Identity Online
B. Federal Identity Organization
C. Flexible ID Option
D. Future Identity Object

10. Zero Trust architecture assumes:
A. Internal network is trusted
B. External network is trusted
C. No implicit trust
D. Trust once, use forever

üî∏ INTERMEDIATE MCQs (10)
11. Which is an example of two-factor authentication?
A. Password + password
B. Password + OTP
C. Username + email
D. PIN + PIN

12. MFA improves security by:
A. Increasing password length
B. Reducing dependency on single factor
C. Encrypting databases
D. Using symmetric keys

13. SSO improves usability but may increase risk because:
A. More encryption
B. Single point of failure
C. Slow authentication
D. Larger key size

14. OAuth allows users to:
A. Share passwords with apps
B. Grant limited access without sharing password
C. Encrypt third-party apps
D. Create certificates

15. OAuth token represents:
A. User password
B. Proof of authorization
C. Encryption key
D. Hash value

16. OpenID Connect is built on top of:
A. SSL
B. OAuth 2.0
C. FTP
D. Kerberos

17. Graphical passwords mainly improve resistance against:
A. Brute force
B. Shoulder surfing
C. Phishing
D. Network sniffing

18. FIDO authentication eliminates the need for:
A. Internet
B. Passwords
C. Cryptography
D. Devices

19. Which is an example of FIDO authenticator?
A. Password file
B. Hardware security key
C. CAPTCHA
D. Firewall

20. Zero Trust requires authentication:
A. Once per session
B. Only at login
C. Continuously
D. Only externally

üî∫ ADVANCED MCQs (10)
21. Which MFA factor is biometrics?
A. Password
B. Smart card
C. Fingerprint
D. OTP

22. OAuth is best described as:
A. Authentication protocol
B. Authorization framework
C. Encryption algorithm
D. Hashing method

23. Risk of graphical passwords includes:
A. Keylogging
B. Guessing via image hotspots
C. Hash collision
D. MITM

24. FIDO uses which cryptographic approach?
A. Symmetric encryption
B. Password hashing
C. Public key cryptography
D. Plaintext keys

25. FIDO improves security by preventing:
A. Replay attacks
B. Password phishing
C. Hash collisions
D. Brute force encryption

26. Zero Trust follows which principle?
A. Trust but verify
B. Verify but trust
C. Never trust, always verify
D. Encrypt and trust

27. Authentication protocols are mainly responsible for:
A. Data encryption
B. Identity verification
C. Network routing
D. File storage

28. Which protocol is commonly used for centralized authentication?
A. FTP
B. LDAP
C. SMTP
D. SNMP

29. Zero Trust architecture focuses on:
A. Network perimeter
B. User identity & device trust
C. Only firewalls
D. VPN only

30. CCEE TRAP in Sessions 11‚Äì12 usually tests:
A. OAuth vs OpenID confusion
B. MFA factor classification
C. Zero Trust philosophy
D. All of the above

‚úÖ ANSWER KEY
Basic:
1.B | 2.A | 3.B | 4.D | 5.B | 6.B | 7.B | 8.B | 9.A | 10.C

Intermediate:
11.B | 12.B | 13.B | 14.B | 15.B | 16.B | 17.B | 18.B | 19.B | 20.C

Advanced:
21.C | 22.B | 23.B | 24.C | 25.B | 26.C | 27.B | 28.B | 29.B | 30.D

üéØ CCEE QUICK REVISION (SESSIONS 11 & 12)
Authentication = identity verification
MFA = something you know + have + are
SSO = convenience + single point of failure
OAuth = authorization, not authentication
OpenID = authentication
FIDO = passwordless, public-key based
Zero Trust = never trust, always verify
